# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# .gitignore for the GASP / ALNS container-loading & knapsack project
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------

# --- Python bytecode and caches ---
__pycache__/
*.py[cod]
*$py.class
*.so

# --- Numba / JIT caches ---
.numba_cache/
__pycache__.numba/

# --- Virtual environments ---
.venv/
venv/
env/
ENV/
.python-version

# --- Packaging / build artifacts ---
build/
dist/
*.egg-info/
*.egg
.eggs/
pip-wheel-metadata/

# --- Test / coverage / type-checker caches ---
.pytest_cache/
.mypy_cache/
.ruff_cache/
.coverage
.coverage.*
htmlcov/
.tox/

# --- Campaign OUTPUTS (regenerated by run_campaign / run_overnight /
#     tune_params / fidelity_run). These are produced by computation and
#     should NOT be versioned: they are large, they change every run, and
#     tracking them would pollute the history. Keep them out of Git and,
#     as we noted, out of any syncing folder while a campaign runs. ---
results/
*.log
overnight.log

# --- Generated workbooks and result files at the repo root ---
Risultati_notte.xlsx
Risultati_*.xlsx
tuning_*.json
fidelity*.json
*.checkpoint.json

# --- Article build artifacts (if the article lives alongside the code) ---
article/node_modules/
article/figs/*.png
article/*.pdf
*.docx#            # LibreOffice/Word lock files
~$*.docx

# --- OS / editor cruft ---
.DS_Store
Thumbs.db
.idea/
.vscode/
*.swp
*~

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# IMPORTANT — what is deliberately NOT ignored (kept in the repo):
#   * gasp/            the package source
#   * examples/        the campaign / runner / tuning / fidelity scripts
#   * tests/           the test suite (must stay green)
#   * data/            the benchmark INSTANCES (BR, ngcut, gcut, okp, ...).
#                      These are the standard literature datasets the paper
#                      relies on; keeping them versioned makes the results
#                      reproducible by anyone who clones the repo. They are
#                      small and static, so they belong in Git.
#   * README.md, ANALISI.md, requirements.txt
#   * article/build_article.js, helpers.js, make_figs.py (the SOURCES that
#     regenerate the document and figures) — the .docx/.pdf/.png outputs
#     are ignored above because they are rebuilt from these sources.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
